BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Tales to Tails
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T233000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T234500Z
UID:698d0a391e64afd01e5ace64@wccls.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Read to a certified therapy dog in a stress-free environment!\
 nSign-up for a 20-minute reading session.\nThis program will help improve 
 your child's reading skills and they get to make a new friend by reading a
 loud to a therapy dog.\nThe dogs and handlers are from\nDove Lewis Portlan
 d Area Canine Therapy Teams\nand\nPet Partners®
LOCATION:Garden Home Community Library\, Enter the building through the Re
 c Center's main entrance and walk through the building to the library and 
 check in at the front desk
URL:https://wccls.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/698d0a391e64afd01e5ace64
X-SOURCE:WCCLS Libraries
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Oregon Humanities Conversation Project: To What Do We Pledge?
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T010000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260416T023000Z
UID:69a09a9eb0595799c09f94fc@wccls.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:While the opening of the Declaration of Independence gets the 
 fanfare and the fireworks—“When in the course of human events” and a
 ll that—the closing clause contains a quiet promise: “We mutually pled
 ge to each other our Lives\, our Fortunes\, and our sacred Honor.” When 
 we talk about the founding\, we often think of it as a severing from a dis
 tant power and a proclamation of individual rights. And yet\, buried in th
 at big individualistic origin story\, there is a pledge of support\, solid
 arity\, and mutual aid. Today\, as we witness political violence\, hostili
 ty\, and polarization\, this conversation invites us to explore what it me
 ans for us to be bound to one another and to ask ourselves: Is there any i
 dea\, any value\, any dream for the future that we care about enough to ti
 e ourselves to one another to protect or pursue it? What would it mean to 
 “mutually pledge” ourselves to one another today? What would it look l
 ike? Feel like? Is it even possible?\nWendy Willis is the founding directo
 r of Oregon's Kitchen Table\, a statewide community engagement program hou
 sed at Portland State University. She is also a poet\, an essayist\, a sti
 tcher\, and a self-proclaimed democracy geek. Wendy was raised in Springfi
 eld\, but now lives with her family in Portland.\nFor adults. Held in the 
 Community Room.
LOCATION:Tualatin Public Library\, Community Room
URL:https://wccls.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a09a9eb0595799c09f94fc
X-SOURCE:WCCLS Libraries
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Navigating Childhood Anxiety and Mood Concerns
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260430T013000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260430T030000Z
UID:69a0ac9d4dacf581ff7e2800@wccls.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:All elementary-aged children experience levels of anxiety and 
 moodiness\, and it can be hard to tell what is “normal." Learn about the
  science underlying anxiety and mood concerns and the various manifestatio
 ns of these conditions. You'll get evidence-based strategies and tools to 
 support your child and family in navigating these concerns with time for Q
 &A. This program is part of our Parent Information Series.\nPresented by: 
 Priya Ramanujam\, Ph.D. & Ellie McLoughlin\, M.A.\, Children's Program.\nT
 his is a hybrid program. You can attend in person or on Zoom.\nAdults only
 .\nRegistration required.
LOCATION:Cedar Mill Library
URL:https://wccls.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a0ac9d4dacf581ff7e2800
X-SOURCE:WCCLS Libraries
END:VEVENT
